a fault, but most of the stress is diffused$\backslash$nthrough aseismic slip. Rapid afterslip on these peripheral areas$\backslash$ncan also produce aftershocks within the main shock rupture area by$\backslash$nreloading weak fault areas that slipped in the main shock and then$\backslash$nhealed. We test this frictional model by comparing the seismicity$\backslash$nand the coseismic slip for the 1966 Parkfield, 1979 Coyote Lake,$\backslash$nand 1984 Morgan Hill earthquakes. The interevent seismicity and aftershocks$\backslash$nappear to occur on fault areas outside the regions of significant$\backslash$nslip: these regions are interpreted as either weak seismic or compliant,$\backslash$ndepending on whether or not they manifest interevent seismicity.},
